article.headline: Georgia clinches first-round bye in SEC tourney
article.linkText: Thomas, Driskell power Georgia past Florida
article.story:
ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- Christi Thomas had 19 points and 10 rebounds
as (No. 16 ESPN/USA Today, No. 14 AP) Georgia beat Florida 76-67, clinching a first-round bye in the Southeastern Conference tournament.
	   
Marquita Driskell added 16 points and 12 rebounds for Georgia (19-8, 10-4 SEC), which can finish no worse than fourth in the league.

	   Vanessa Hayden led Florida (9-17, 1-13 SEC) with 20 points and
five blocked shots. She did not play against Georgia in January,
when the Lady Dogs won by 43 points at Gainesville, Fla.

	   Hayden helped Florida stay closer to Georgia this time, but the
Gators never led. They came closest with 6:15 to play in the first
half when Hayden completed a three-point play to narrow the gap to
19-18. Florida had two opportunities to take the lead but the Lady
Dogs closed out the half with a 12-1 run.

	   Georgia stretched the lead to 42-25 after Alexis Kendrick's
putback with 17:21 to play. Two straight 3-pointers by Florida's
Kelly Stevenson closed the Gators to within 11, but Georgia took
the game inside to Thomas and Driskell to push the margin to 58-39.

	   All five Georgia starters scored in double figures, including
Kendrick with 11, Mary Beth Lycett with 10 and Sherill Baker with
10.

	   Sarah Lowe and Tamia Williams scored 11 each for Florida, which
finished with its worst regular-season record since 1987-88 when
the Gators were 9-18.
